Defines the `ctx-scan` CLI surface (via `clap`) and the mode-dispatch logic that routes to `runner.rs`'s scan/check/prune/update functions; this is the entry point an editor changes when adding a new run mode or CLI flag.

Modes are mutually exclusive by construction — `Mode` uses `clap`'s `conflicts_with_all` so `--dry-run`, `--check`, `--update` can't combine, and `--stop-hook`/`--prune` are excluded from all of them at the `Cli` level. Adding a new mode means updating both the `conflicts_with_all` lists on existing fields and the dispatch logic in `dispatch`/`stop_hook`/`prune`, or the exclusivity silently breaks.

`stop_hook` is deliberately agent-free and always fail-open: it recomputes staleness and, if stale, writes a `{"systemMessage": ...}` JSON payload to `out`, emitting nothing on a fresh tree. Comment explains why regeneration doesn't happen here — Claude Code's Stop event fires per-turn, not per-session, so billing an agent call here would race the session; the binary is expected to treat any `Err` from this path as "say nothing."

`prompts` resolves relative to the process cwd, not the scanned `dir` — a common footgun when running `ctx-scan` from a different working directory than the target.

Key entry points: `list_targets`, `check`, `prune`, `stop_hook`, `dispatch` — all take `&Cli` (or `&Path` for `stop_hook`) plus a generic `W: Write` for output, and an `A: Agent` for `dispatch` only. `validate_dir` is the shared private gate: canonicalizes and errors `ScanError::DirNotFound` if not a directory — called by every public entry point before touching `runner`/`walker`.